  "texts": [
    "Box 2 describes some commonly used metrics used for measuring edge strength and determining the selection process.",
    "Each approach includes some form of adjustment to account for the prevalence of each disease (49).",
    "Two commonly used measures of edge strength are the relative risk (RR) and the Phi (ϕ) correlation.",
    "These each have their separate advantages and disadvantages, including biases toward either rare or highly prevalent diseases (32), and are therefore sometimes presented together.",
    "For example, when creating the phenotypic disease network (PDN) to explore disease progression using the ICD-9 codes from more than 32 million inpatient claims, the strength of comorbidity relationships was quantified using both the RR and ϕ correlation, with edges retained based on a RR > 20 or a ϕ correlation >0.06 (23)."
  ],
